Introduction¶

Adolescent health remains a critical, yet often overlooked, area of global public health.
This report focuses on mortality among adolescents aged 10–14 years, using UNICEF's global dataset to highlight key patterns and inequalities.

In this report, we will explore:

  • The top countries with the highest adolescent mortality rates
  • Mortality rate trends over time in selected countries
  • A global view of mortality distribution through mapping
  • Key recommendations for future health policies

Understanding and addressing adolescent mortality is essential for achieving global development goals and building a healthier future generation.

Mortality Rates by Gender in Top 10 Countries¶

The chart below compares mortality rates between male and female adolescents (ages 10–14) in the top 10 countries with the highest overall mortality.

Key Observations:

  • In most countries, male adolescents show slightly higher mortality rates than female adolescents.
  • The gender gap is significant in some regions, while in others it is minimal or even reversed.
  • These patterns reflect complex influences of biological, social, and healthcare factors on adolescent survival.
In [ ]:
# Step 1: Filter latest year
latest_year = data['time_period'].max()
latest_data = data[data['time_period'] == latest_year]

# Step 2: Remove 'Both sexes'
latest_data = latest_data[latest_data['sex'].isin(['Male', 'Female'])]

# Step 3: Pick top 10 countries (overall highest average mortality)
top10_countries = latest_data.groupby('country')['obs_value'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).head(10).index.tolist()

# Step 4: Filter top 10 countries only
top10_gender_data = latest_data[latest_data['country'].isin(top10_countries)]

# Step 5: Plot
(
    ggplot(top10_gender_data) +
    aes(x='country', y='obs_value', fill='sex') +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge') +  # side-by-side bars
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
        title='Adolescent Mortality Rate by Gender – Top 10 Countries (Age 10–14)',
        x='Country',
        y='Mortality Rate (per 1,000)',
        fill='Sex'
    ) +
    theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=16, face="bold"),
        axis_title_x=element_text(size=12),
        axis_title_y=element_text(size=12),
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1),
        axis_text_y=element_text(size=10)
    )
)

Global Distribution of Adolescent Mortality¶

The map below visualizes adolescent mortality rates across countries.

Higher mortality rates are concentrated in low- and middle-income regions, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa and parts of South Asia, highlighting ongoing inequalities in global health access and outcomes.

Gender and Economic Disparities in Adolescent Mortality¶

The scatterplot below illustrates the relationship between GDP per capita and adolescent mortality rates, separated by gender.

Key Insights:

  • Mortality rates tend to decrease with increasing national wealth.
  • Males often exhibit slightly higher mortality rates compared to females across GDP levels.
  • In wealthier countries, gender differences in mortality narrow significantly, indicating more equitable access to healthcare resources.

# Merge mortality with GDP from metadata
data['country'] = data['country'].str.strip().str.title()
metadata['country'] = metadata['country'].str.strip().str.title()

# Merge datasets
merged_data = pd.merge(data, metadata[['country', 'gdp per capita (constant 2015 us$)']], on='country', how='left')

# Rename GDP column
merged_data.rename(columns={'gdp per capita (constant 2015 us$)': 'gdp'}, inplace=True)

# Filter for latest year
latest_gender_data = merged_data[(merged_data['time_period'] == latest_year) & (merged_data['sex'].isin(['Male', 'Female']))]

# Drop rows with missing GDP
latest_gender_data = latest_gender_data.dropna(subset=['gdp'])
In [ ]:
# Create GDP Bands
bins = [0, 1000, 5000, 10000, 50000, 1000000]
labels = ['<1k', '1k-5k', '5k-10k', '10k-50k', '>50k']

latest_gender_data['gdp_band'] = pd.cut(latest_gender_data['gdp'], bins=bins, labels=labels)

# Group by GDP Band and Sex
avg_mortality = latest_gender_data.groupby(['gdp_band', 'sex'])['obs_value'].mean().reset_index()

# Plot Line Chart
(
    ggplot(avg_mortality) +
    aes(x='gdp_band', y='obs_value', group='sex', color='sex') +
    geom_line(size=2) +
    geom_point(size=3) +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
        title='Average Adolescent Mortality Rate vs GDP Band (by Gender)',
        x='GDP per Capita Band',
        y='Average Mortality Rate (per 1,000)',
        color='Gender'
    ) +
    theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=16, face="bold"),
        axis_title_x=element_text(size=12),
        axis_title_y=element_text(size=12),
        axis_text_x=element_text(size=10, rotation=45, hjust=1),
        axis_text_y=element_text(size=10),
        legend_title=element_text(size=12),
        legend_text=element_text(size=10)
    )

Conclusion¶

This report analyzed global adolescent mortality rates (ages 10–14) using UNICEF datasets, focusing on gender differences, regional disparities, and economic influences.

Key Findings:

  • Top Risk Countries: Countries with the highest adolescent mortality rates are mainly concentrated in Sub-Saharan Africa and parts of South Asia, reflecting persistent healthcare and socio-economic inequalities.
  • Gender Disparities: Across most income levels, male adolescents tend to have slightly higher mortality rates than females, although the gap narrows in wealthier countries.
  • Economic Influence: Higher national GDP per capita is strongly associated with lower adolescent mortality rates, confirming that economic development plays a crucial role in improving youth survival.
  • Global Distribution: The global map visualization highlights stark differences between low- and high-income regions, emphasizing the urgency for targeted health interventions.

Recommendations:

  • Focus international healthcare resources on the most vulnerable regions.
  • Strengthen early interventions and education targeted at adolescents.
  • Promote global collaborations to reduce gender disparities and ensure equitable access to healthcare services for all adolescents.

Investing in adolescent health today will shape healthier, more resilient generations tomorrow.
